english:
  title: The Biography of the Bamboo Lady
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Lady bore the surname Bamboo and was named Ping, daughter of Yun of the Wei riverside. Her lineage descended from the ancient Cang-tang clan, whose ancestors understood the music of heaven. The Yellow Emperor himself selected them to govern the rituals of sound, and the pipes of the age of Yu were born of their line. From the shadow of Kunlun Mountain, the Cang-tang migrated eastward. In the time of Fu Xi, together with the Wei clan, they preserved the written word and achieved great renown. Their descendants maintained the duty of historians through the ages. When the Qin brought cruelty upon the land, employing the schemes of Li Si, they burned the books and buried the scholars. The descendants of Cang-tang faded into obscurity. In the Han dynasty, there came a paper-maker named Chu, a guest of Cai Lun, who had learned something of letters and brush. He often played among the Bamboo clan, yet his nature was shallow and he delighted in whispered slanders. Envying the Bamboo clan's uprightness, he secretly gnawed away at their reputation and robbed them of their position.

    In the Zhou dynasty lived Rod, also of the Bamboo line. He fished with Duke Tai Gong at the Wei riverside. When Duke Tai Gong fashioned a hook, Rod spoke thus: "I have heard that the greatest fishing requires no hook at all. The size of the catch depends upon the curve and the straight. What is straight can catch kingdoms; what is curved catches only fish." Duke Tai Gong heeded these words, and later became the teacher of King Wen, receiving the domain of Qi. For recognizing Rod's worthiness, the Wei riverside became his fief, and this is how the Bamboo clan came to flourish there. Their descendants remain numerous to this day—such as Leaves, Joints, Strips, and Slats in their various forms. Those who migrated to Yang province are called Twigs and Stalks; those who went among the northern peoples are called Woven Mats. The Bamboo clan possessed both civil and martial gifts, generation after generation serving in ritual vessels, musical instruments, and the implements of warfare and hunting, all recorded in the histories for all to witness.

    Only Stump possessed a dull nature, with a blocked heart that refused learning until death came. When Yun came of age, he withdrew from the world and took no office. He had one brother named Tube, equal in name and nature to himself—hollow within yet true in bearing. Tube became close friends with Wang Ziyou, who said of him, "Not a single day can pass without this gentleman," and so he was called "This Gentleman." Since Ziyou was himself a man of principle in choosing his companions, one could know his friend's true worth.

    Tube married the daughter of Mother-of-Benefit and fathered one daughter—she who became this Lady. In her maiden years, she possessed the bearing of virtue and purity. A neighbor named Auspicious Male composed wanton verses to test her, but the Lady grew wrathful and declared: "Though man and woman differ, their duty to honor is one. If once bent by another's hand, how can one stand upright in the world again?" Auspicious Male departed in shame—could such a one even hope to rival the herder of oxen?

    When she reached womanhood, Sir Pine sought her hand with proper courtesy. Her parents said, "Sir Pine is a gentleman of true character. His lifelong bearing matches our family's own." And so they sent her to be his wife. The Lady's nature grew ever more steadfast and profound. When circumstances demanded discernment, her judgments came swift and clean as a blade through silk. Even the constancy of Maiden Plum and the silence of the Li clan could not sway her gaze—how much less Aged Orange or Young Apricot? On misty mornings and moonlit evenings, she would sing with the wind and whistle through the rain, her elegant bearing beyond all description. Those fond of such things secretly sketched her likeness and treasured it as precious. Such masters as Wen Yu-ke and Su Shi were especially devoted to her image.

    Sir Pine was eighteen years her senior. In his later years, he pursued the way of immortals and wandered to Grain-Stone Mountain, where he turned to stone and never returned. The Lady dwelt alone, and often sang the songs of Wei, her heart trembling and beyond her own steadying. Yet her nature loved wine deeply. The records have lost the year, but on the thirteenth day of the fifth moon, she moved her household to Green-Basin Mountain. There, overcome by drink, she contracted a wasting illness that would not heal. From that sickness onward, she lived depending on others' kindness, yet in her final years grew only more steadfast, earning the respect of all her locality. The Regional Commander Yu-Qian, who shared her surname Bamboo, heard of her conduct and reported it above, whereupon she received the title of Virtuous Widow.

    The Historian spoke thus: "The Bamboo clan's ancestors achieved great deeds in ancient times. Their descendants have all possessed talent and steadfast honor, spoken of in the world. The Lady's virtue was fitting to her line. Yet—having been matched with a gentleman and becoming the stay of others, she departed childless. Is it not proven that Heaven knows nothing?"
  footnotes:
    - 'Wei feng (衛風): One of the sections of the Classic of Poetry, often associated with melancholy and longing.'
    - 'The text employs extensive plant and insect metaphors: paper-maker as harmful insect (Chu/楮), various bamboo names referencing their forms and uses, Orange and Apricot as references to other legendary faithful women.'
    - Stone transformation and Daoist immortality (Grain-Stone Mountain) were common tropes in Chinese literature suggesting transcendence beyond the mortal realm.
    - The concluding lament about Heaven's indifference to virtue and childlessness reflects Buddhist and philosophical themes about the injustice of fate.
